00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:54.230
It's not that naïve at all.
 

00:35:54.230 --> 00:35:55.260
Let me show you why.
 

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:58.253
Here's the book by
J.J. Thomson called The

00:35:58.253 --> 00:36:01.722
Corpuscular Theory of
Matter, and if you look in

00:36:01.722 --> 00:36:05.260
there you'll find out what he's
talking about.

00:36:05.260 --> 00:36:09.469
He says -- he has a model of
electron configuration --

00:36:09.469 --> 00:36:12.586
he says: "Consider the
problem of how to arrange 1,2,

00:36:12.586 --> 00:36:14.391
3, up to n
corpuscles"

00:36:14.391 --> 00:36:16.469
(that's what he called
electrons,

00:36:16.469 --> 00:36:20.958
he called them corpuscles);
"Consider the problem as

00:36:20.958 --> 00:36:25.929
to how they would arrange
themselves if placed in a sphere

00:36:25.929 --> 00:36:31.250
filled with positive electricity
of uniform density."

00:36:31.250 --> 00:36:32.900
So that's the idea of the
plum-pudding.

00:36:32.900 --> 00:36:36.929
You have this sphere of uniform
positive density --

00:36:36.929 --> 00:36:39.739
why it should be like that
nobody knows --

00:36:39.739 --> 00:36:42.947
but suppose you have a sphere,
and you put the electrons in

00:36:42.947 --> 00:36:44.994
it,
like plums in a plum-pudding,

00:36:44.994 --> 00:36:47.239
which is like a fruitcake in
England.

00:36:47.239 --> 00:36:53.023
Okay, now notice that he said,
"placed in a sphere

00:36:53.023 --> 00:36:56.909
filled with positive
electricity."

00:36:56.909 --> 00:36:59.460
Why did he do that?
 

00:36:59.460 --> 00:37:02.427
Why didn't he just have -- like
