patterns --
sometimes you get three inside

00:41:26.565 --> 00:41:28.376
eight,
sometimes you get two inside

00:41:28.376 --> 00:41:29.599
nine, for that number.
 

00:41:29.599 --> 00:41:32.840
Okay, and then you can get four
inside nine,

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:35.248
four inside ten,
five inside ten,

00:41:35.248 --> 00:41:38.994
and then after five,
if you put in more,

00:41:38.994 --> 00:41:44.505
if you put in sixteen,
you get one inside five inside

00:41:44.505 --> 00:41:45.000
ten.
 

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.070
What is this reminding you of?
 

00:41:47.070 --> 00:41:47.699
Yes?
 

00:41:47.699 --> 00:41:48.860
Student:  Of orbitals.
 

00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:51.400
Prof: The shell
structure of atoms.

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:52.570
Right?
 

00:41:52.570 --> 00:41:55.300
As you go down the periodic
table you complete a shell.

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:58.126
So it's a model of shells,
and then you can get more and

00:41:58.126 --> 00:41:58.949
more and more.
 

00:41:58.949 --> 00:42:04.340
So this is what Thomson was
thinking about.

00:42:04.340 --> 00:42:06.309
But that's just two dimensions.
 

00:42:06.309 --> 00:42:06.820
Right?
 

00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:08.309
Three dimensions is a bigger
problem.

00:42:08.309 --> 00:42:11.599
But he could say,
he was able to say something

00:42:11.599 --> 00:42:13.719
mathematically about eight.
 

00:42:13.719 --> 00:42:17.920
"The equilibrium of eight
corpuscles at the corners of a

00:42:17.920 --> 00:42:19.670
cube is unstable."
 

00:42:19.670 --> 00:42:22.791
Even if you have the spherical
charge -- so it's not exactly

00:42:22.791 --> 00:42:26.230
Earnshaw -- still you can't get
eight at the corners of a cube.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:30.409
Now Lewis comes alon,g and in
1923,

00:42:30.409 --> 00:42:33.952
as I've told you before,
he writes: "I have ever

00:42:33.952 --> 00:42:38.108
since regarded the cubic octet
as representing essentially the

00:42:38.108 --> 00:42:41.309
arrangement of electrons in the
atom."

00:42:41.309 --> 00:42:44.956
This is long after Thomson had
written this about not being

00:42:44.956 --> 00:42:46.090
able to do that.
 

00:42:46.090 --> 00:42:50.610
So was Lewis ignorant of
Earnshaw's theorem?

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:55.204
Because by 1923 they know that
the nucleus is not a

00:42:55.204 --> 00:43:00.440
plum-pudding -- that is the
positive sphere -- that it's a

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:01.360
point.
 

00:43:01.360 --> 00:43:04.570
So was Lewis just naïve?
 

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:08.050
No, look what he wrote, in 1916.
 

00:43:08.050 --> 00:43:11.594
"The electric forces
between particles which are very

00:43:11.594 --> 00:43:15.324
close together do not obey the
simple laws of inverse-squares

00:43:15.324 --> 00:43:18.000
which holds at greater
distances."

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.619
So Coulomb's law breaks down.
 

00:43:20.619 --> 00:43:22.900
You don't have inverse-square.
 

00:43:22.900 --> 00:43:25.190
So then you don't have
Earnshaw's theorem,

00:43:25.190 --> 00:43:28.429
and you don't have to worry,
and you can get a structure if

00:43:28.429 --> 00:43:30.719
it's not an inverse-square force
law.

00:43:30.719 --> 00:43:31.570
Okay?
 

00:43:31.570 --> 00:43:32.079
No trouble.
 

00:43:32.079 --> 00:43:33.369
But what is the force law?
 

00:43:33.369 --> 00:43:36.748
Well Thomson thought the same
thing in 1923 in his book The

00:43:36.748 --> 00:43:38.300
Electron in Chemistry.
 

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:41.849
He wrote: "If electron
nuclear attraction were to vary

00:43:41.849 --> 00:43:45.492
strictly as the inverse-square,
we know by Earnshaw's theorem

00:43:45.492 --> 00:43:48.780
that no stable configuration is
possible with the electrons at

00:43:48.780 --> 00:43:51.851
rest or oscillating about
positions of equilibriumâ€¦

00:43:51.851 --> 00:43:55.137
I shall assume that the law of
force between a positive charge

00:43:55.137 --> 00:43:57.940
and an electron is expressed by
this equationâ€¦

00:43:57.940 --> 00:44:00.905
Then a number of electrons can
be in equilibrium about a

00:44:00.905 --> 00:44:03.706
positive charge without
necessarily describing orbits

00:44:03.706 --> 00:44:05.268
around it."
 

00:44:05.268 --> 00:44:07.914
And look at the -- we're going
to end right now by looking at

00:44:07.914 --> 00:44:08.619
this equation.
 

00:44:08.619 --> 00:44:10.784
What's that bit of it,
the first bit,

00:44:10.784 --> 00:44:12.409
the "one"
part?

00:44:12.409 --> 00:44:13.260
Students:  Coulomb's law.
 

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:15.639
Prof: That's Coulomb's
law.

00:44:15.639 --> 00:44:18.389
But he's got a correction to
Coulomb's law,

00:44:18.389 --> 00:44:22.719
here at the end,
c/r, where c is a distance --

00:44:22.719 --> 00:44:25.110
you divide it by r and you get
a number --

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:30.179
and c is a distance that's on
the scale of atomic lengths.

00:44:30.179 --> 00:44:30.909
Right?
 

00:44:30.909 --> 00:44:36.349
And that means that as long as
c is very small -- pardon me,

00:44:36.349 --> 00:44:40.590
as long as -- okay so have I
got this right?

00:44:40.590 --> 00:44:46.458
Okay, so when distance r gets
smaller than c,

00:44:46.458 --> 00:44:50.460
then the force changes sign.
 

00:44:50.460 --> 00:44:51.360
Okay?
 

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:54.867
So what was attractive becomes
repulsive, and then you can have

00:44:54.867 --> 00:44:57.300
the electrons sitting around the
nucleus.

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:58.739
Okay?
 

00:44:58.739 --> 00:45:02.699
So we'll see what happened
three years later next time.

